This is one of the most common points of confusion with ThreadLocal. The behavior you're seeing isn't a bug—it’s actually the core "safety net" feature of how ThreadLocal works!
Here is why you see "abc" instead of null at line 17:
1. The Role of initialValue()
When you created your ThreadLocal at line 5, you didn't just create a variable; you provided a Blueprint (the initialValue() method).
This blueprint tells Java: "Whenever this thread doesn't have a value in its pocket, give it 'abc' by default."
2. The Step-by-Step Logic
Let's trace your code exactly:
 * Line 13 (tl.get()): The thread looks in its pocket. It's empty. It calls your initialValue() method. It gets "abc".
 * Line 14 (tl.set("durga")): You manually put "durga" into the thread's pocket. The "abc" is ignored for now.
 * Line 15 (tl.get()): It looks in its pocket, finds "durga", and prints it.
 * Line 16 (tl.remove()): You explicitly empty the pocket. The value "durga" is gone.
 * Line 17 (tl.get()): The thread looks in its pocket again. It is empty.
> Crucial Part: Because the pocket is empty, Java behaves exactly like it did at Line 13. It triggers the initialValue() method again to "refill" the pocket with your default value.
> 
3. How to get null instead
If your goal was to see null after calling .remove(), you would need to define the ThreadLocal without overriding initialValue().
// If you do it this way:
ThreadLocal tl = new ThreadLocal(); 

tl.set("durga");
tl.remove();
System.out.println(tl.get()); // THIS will now print null

Summary of the "Life Cycle"
| Action | Thread's Internal Storage | Result of get() |
|---|---|---|
| New ThreadLocal | Empty | Calls initialValue() -> abc |
| .set("durga") | Has "durga" | Returns durga |
| .remove() | Empty | Calls initialValue() -> abc |
Why does Java do this?
This is designed for things like Database Connections or User Sessions. If a thread finishes a task and clears its session (remove()), you want the next time it asks for a session to get a fresh, default starting point—not a dangerous NullPointerException.
